      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The strongest argument against race-conscious hiring is that it inherently violates the principle of pure meritocracy, which demands that individuals be judged solely on their skills and abilities, irrespective of their background. Proponents of this view argue that any deviation based on race introduces arbitrary classifications that undermine the fairness of the hiring process. Furthermore, they contend that such policies can lead to reverse discrimination, where qualified candidates are passed over based on immutable characteristics rather than performance. This perspective maintains that true organizational excellence is achieved only when selection criteria are entirely race-blind and competency-focused.",
      "source": "target",
